**Install:** download one `.js` file. That's it. No `npm install`. No build step. Node 18+ and macOS are the only requirements.

## What it does

It exposes 14 tools to Claude:

- `open_url`, `new_tab`, `close_current_tab`, `reload_page`, `go_back`, `go_forward`
- `get_current_tab`, `list_tabs`, `activate_tab`
- `get_page_text`, `get_page_html`
- `run_javascript` — arbitrary JS in the active tab, returns the result
- `search` — google / duckduckgo / bing / brave
- `take_screenshot` — PNG of the front Safari window

So you can say things like:

> *"Open Hacker News and tell me the top three story titles."*
> *"In the active tab, count the number of `<a>` tags."*
> *"Take a screenshot of the page and save it to ~/Desktop."*

…and Claude does it inside *your* Safari, with *your* sessions, *your* cookies, *your* logged-in accounts.

## Why piggyback on real Safari instead of headless Chromium?

- **Sessions just work.** No re-logging into Gmail, GitHub, your bank, your cloud console. The agent inherits whatever you're already authenticated for.
- **Native macOS perf.** `osascript` + a single Node process. Idle RAM is rounding error.
- **You can watch it work.** The agent's actions happen in a window you can see, intervene in, and trust.
- **No vendored browser.** Nothing to update. Apple ships Safari for you.

The tradeoff: macOS only. If you need cross-platform, [puppeteer-mcp](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/servers) is the right tool. This is for people who live in Safari.

## How it's built

The server is one file (`safari-mcp.js`, ~300 lines) that implements MCP's JSON-RPC 2.0 stdio protocol by hand — no `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` dependency. Browser control routes through:

- **AppleScript** for tab and window operations (`tell application "Safari" ...`)
- **JXA (JavaScript for Automation)** for richer reads like enumerating tabs across windows
- **Safari's `do JavaScript`** for `run_javascript`, gated behind the standard "Allow JavaScript from Apple Events" Develop-menu opt-in

Adding a new tool is literally one entry in the `TOOLS` array.

## Setup

```bash
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<your-username>/claude-safari-mcp/main/safari-mcp.js
```

Claude Desktop — edit `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json`:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "safari": {
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["/absolute/path/to/safari-mcp.js"]
    }
  }
}
```

Claude Code:

```bash
claude mcp add safari -- node /absolute/path/to/safari-mcp.js
```

First call triggers macOS's Automation permission prompt — approve once and you're done.

## What's next

- Reader-mode text extraction (cleaner than `innerText`)
- Bookmarks + Reading List read APIs
- Per-tab screenshots
- Form-fill helpers on top of `run_javascript`
- Streaming URL changes back to Claude as MCP resources

Issues, PRs, weird ideas all welcome. The whole codebase is one file — fork it and tweak.

**MIT licensed.** Built in an evening. Hope it saves you a few logins.

